    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.75-76_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">75</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>The Faces of a Young Man and Woman, in Profile</figDesc>
                        <p>THE SCHOOL THAT LIVES ON FAITH THE SCHOOL OF THE OZARKS 1906 POINT LOOKOUT, MISSOURI&#8212;NEAR HOLLISTER, MO.</p>
                    </figure>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">
                        VOCATIONAL
                            <lb/>
                        CULTURAL
                            <lb/>
                        SPIRITUAL
                            <lb/>
                        
                        R.M. GOOD. PRESIDENT EMERITUS                   M. GRAHAM CLARK, PRESIDENT
                            <lb/>
                        
                        THE SCHOOL OF THE OZARKS
                            <lb/>
                        "A MOUNTAIN SCHOOL FOR BOYS AND GIRLS"
                            <lb/>
                        
                        POINT LOOKOUT, MISSOURI
                            <lb/>
                        FREIGHT &amp; EXPRESS OFFICE - HOLLISTER, MO.
                    </hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 8, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Professor of English</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>University of Missouri</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>We were distressed beyond measure to learn of the death of Mrs. Neihardt. We wish to extend to you and to your son and daughters our deepest os<sic>of</sic> sympathy in the loss of your helpmate for these many, many years. She was truly a wonderfully fine and good woman, and I was happy to have had the pleasure and privilege of knowing her. She was fortunate in having so many fine talents which were so fitting with your brilliant life of doing things worthwhile in the world.</p>
                
                <p>We have thought of you many times during these hours. We know that your grief will be softened through the years by the happy memory of her rich and full life. God has been good to us in that while He takes away from us those who are nearest and dearest to us, yet He leaves them with us in our minds and hearts. We know that God is too wise to err and too good to be unkind and in His infinite wisdom, He doeth all things well.</p>
                
                <p>I have a little prayer which I think is very fitting for such a life as that of Mrs. Neihardt's, and I am enclosing it in this letter.</p>
                
                <p>We want to assure you again of our deep sympathy. With warmest regards and highest esteem, I am</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>R M Good</signed>
                
                    <hi rend="caps">THE SCHOOL OF THE OZARKS</hi>
                
                    <note>RMGood/fm</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
